# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hal-hypermedia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] With HATEOAS, a client interacts with a network application whose application servers provide information dynamically through hypermedia.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] A REST client needs little to no prior knowledge about how to interact with an application or server beyond a generic understanding of hypermedia.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] By contrast, clients and servers in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA) interact through a fixed interface shared through documentation or an interface description language (IDL).
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The restrictions imposed by HATEOAS decouple client and server.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] This enables server functionality to evolve independently.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The term was coined in 2000 by Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] A user-agent makes an HTTP request to a REST API through an entry point URL.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] All subsequent requests the user-agent may make are discovered inside the response to each request.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The media types used for these representations, and the link relations they may contain, are part of the API.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The client transitions through application states by selecting from the links within a representation or by manipulating the representation in other ways afforded by its media type.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] In this way, RESTful interaction is driven by hypermedia, rather than out-of-band information.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The response contains these possible follow-up links: POST a deposit, withdrawal, transfer, or close request (to close the account).
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] As an example, later, after the account has been overdrawn, there is a different set of available links, because the account is overdrawn.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] Now only one link is available: to deposit more money (by POSTing to deposits).
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] In its current *state*, the other links are not available.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] Hence the term *Engine of Application State*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] What actions are possible varies as the state of the resource varies.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] A client does not need to understand every media type and communication mechanism offered by the server.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The ability to understand new media types may be acquired at run-time through "code-on-demand" provided to the client by the server.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The HATEOAS constraint is an essential part of the "uniform interface" feature of REST, as defined in Roy Fielding's doctoral dissertation.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] Fielding has further described the concept on his blog.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] The purpose of some of the strictness of this and other REST constraints, Fielding explains, is "software design on the scale of decades: every detail is intended to promote software longevity and independent evolution.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] Many of the constraints are directly opposed to short-term efficiency.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hateoas] Unfortunately, people are fairly good at short-term design, and usually awful at long-term design".
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In computing, a **hyperlink**, or simply a **link**, is a digital reference providing direct access to data by a user's clicking or tapping.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A hyperlink points to a whole document or to a specific element within a document.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The text that is linked from is known as anchor text.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A software system that is used for viewing and creating hypertext is a *hypertext system*, and to create a hyperlink is *to hyperlink* (or simply *to link*).
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A user following hyperlinks is said to *navigate* or *browse* the hypertext.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The document containing a hyperlink is known as its source document.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] For example, in content from Wikipedia or Google Search, many words and terms in the text are hyperlinked to definitions of those terms.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Hyperlinks are often used to implement reference mechanisms such as tables of contents, footnotes, bibliographies, indexes, and glossaries.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In some hypertext, hyperlinks can be bidirectional: they can be followed in two directions, so both ends act as anchors and as targets.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] More complex arrangements exist, such as many-to-many links.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Another possibility is transclusion, for which the link target is a document fragment that replaces the link anchor within the source document.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Not only persons browsing the document may follow hyperlinks.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] These hyperlinks may also be followed automatically by programs.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A program that traverses the hypertext, following each hyperlink and gathering all the retrieved documents is known as a Web *spider* or crawler.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] An inline link displays remote content without the need for embedding the content.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The remote content may be accessed with or without the user following the link.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] An inline link may display a modified version of the content; for instance, instead of an image, a thumbnail, low resolution preview, cropped section, or magnified section may be shown.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The full content is then usually available on demand, as is the case with print publishing software – e.g., with an external link.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] This allows for smaller file sizes and quicker response to changes when the full linked content is not needed, as is the case when rearranging a page layout.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] An anchor hyperlink (anchor link) is a link bound to a portion of a document, which is often called a fragment.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The fragment is generally a portion of text or a heading, though not necessarily.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] For instance, it may also be a *hot area* in an image (image map in HTML), a designated, often irregular part of an image.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Fragments are marked with *anchors* (in any of various ways), which is why a link to a fragment is called an anchor link (that is, a link to an anchor).
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] For example, in XML, the element `<anchor id="name" />"` provides anchoring capability (as long as the DTD or schema defines it), and in wiki markup, `{{anchor|name}}` is a typical example of implementing it.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In word processor apps, anchors can be inserted where desired and may be called *bookmarks*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In URLs, the hash character (#) precedes the name of the anchor for the fragment.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] One way to define a hot area in an image is by a list of coordinates that indicate its boundaries.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] For example, a political map of Africa may have each country hyperlinked to further information about that country.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A separate invisible hot area interface allows for swapping skins or labels within the linked hot areas without repetitive embedding of links in the various skin elements.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A **fat link** (also known as a "one-to-many" link, an "extended link" or a "multi-tailed link") is a hyperlink which leads to multiple endpoints; the link is a set-valued function.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Tim Berners-Lee saw the possibility of using hyperlinks to link any information to any other information over the Internet.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Hyperlinks were therefore integral to the creation of the World Wide Web.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Web pages are written in the hypertext mark-up language HTML.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Webgraph is a graph, formed from web pages as vertices and hyperlinks, as directed edges.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The W3C recommendation called XLink describes hyperlinks that offer a far greater degree of functionality than those offered in HTML.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] These **extended links** can be *multidirectional*, remove linking from, within, and between XML documents.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] It can also describe *simple links*, which are unidirectional and therefore offer no more functionality than hyperlinks in HTML.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Permalinks are URLs that are intended to remain unchanged for many years into the future, yielding hyperlinks that are less susceptible to link rot.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Permalinks are often rendered simply, that is, as friendly URLs, so as to be easy for people to type and remember.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Permalinks are used in order to point and redirect readers to the same Web page, blog post or any online digital media.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The scientific literature is a place where link persistence is crucial to the public knowledge.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A 2013 study in BMC Bioinformatics analyzed 15,000 links in abstracts from Thomson Reuters' Web of Science citation index, founding that the median lifespan of Web pages was 9.3 years, and just 62% were archived.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The median lifespan of a Web page constitutes high-degree variable, but its order of magnitude usually is of some months.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] An *Internet shortcut* file, also known as the URL file format, has the file extension .url (possibly hidden by default in the graphical user interface), and is the file format in Windows systems used for hyperlinks to the Internet.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Internet shortcuts are text files, but their internal structure is similar to that of an INI file.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Opening them in the graphical file browser of Windows or macOS (but not Linux) will open the link in the default web browser.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Internet shortcut files can be easily made by hand, as the minimum features needed to operate as a hyperlink are simply the `[InternetShortcut]` header and the `URL=` key-value pair.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Other key-value pairs are irregularly supported across operating systems.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] On macOS systems, the specialized file format for file based hyperlinks is the .webloc file.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A file based hyperlink under Unix/Linux with a desktop environment is stored in a .desktop file.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] It is a text file with a syntax highly similar to the Windows `URL` file described above.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A link from one domain to another is said to be *outbound* from its source anchor and *inbound* to its target.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The most common destination anchor is a URL used in the World Wide Web.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] This can refer to a document, e.g. a webpage, or other resource, or to a position in a webpage.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The latter is achieved by means of an HTML element with a "name" or "id" attribute at that position of the HTML document.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The URL of the position is the URL of the webpage with a fragment identifier – "#*id attribute*" – appended.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] When linking to PDF documents from an HTML page the "*id attribute*" can be replaced with syntax that references a page number or another element of the PDF, for example, "#*page=386*".
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] A web browser usually displays a hyperlink in some distinguishing way, e.g. in a different color, font or style, or with certain symbols following to visualize link target or document types.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The behavior and style of links can be specified using the Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) language.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In a graphical user interface, the appearance of a mouse cursor may change into a hand motif to indicate a link.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In most graphical web browsers, links are displayed in underlined blue text when they have not been visited, but underlined purple text when they have.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] When the user activates the link (e.g., by clicking on it with the mouse) the browser displays the link's target.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] If the target is not an HTML file, depending on the file type and on the browser and its plugins, another program may be activated to open the file.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In a typical web browser, this would display as the underlined word "Example" in blue, which when clicked would take the user to the example.com website.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] This contributes to a clean, easy to read text or document.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Mozilla Firefox, IE, Opera, and many other web browsers all show the URL.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In addition, the URL is commonly shown in the status bar.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Normally, a link opens in the current frame or window, but sites that use frames and multiple windows for navigation can add a special "target" attribute to specify where the link loads.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] If no window exists with that name, a new window is created with the ID, which can be used to refer to the window later in the browsing session.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Creation of new windows is probably the most common use of the "target" attribute.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] To prevent accidental reuse of a window, the special window names "_blank" and "_new" are usually available, and always cause a new window to be created.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] It is especially common to see this type of link when one large website links to an external page.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The intention in that case is to ensure that the person browsing is aware that there is no endorsement of the site being linked to by the site that was linked from.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] However, the attribute is sometimes overused and can sometimes cause many windows to be created even while browsing a single site.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Another special page name is "_top", which causes any frames in the current window to be cleared away so that browsing can continue in the full window.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The term "link" was coined in 1965 (or possibly 1964) by Ted Nelson at the start of Project Xanadu.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Nelson had been inspired by "As We May Think", a popular 1945 essay by Vannevar Bush.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In the essay, Bush described a microfilm-based machine (the Memex) in which one could link any two pages of information into a "trail" of related information, and then scroll back and forth among pages in a trail as if they were on a single microfilm reel.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Though Nelson's Xanadu Corporation was eventually funded by Autodesk in the 1980s, it never created this proprietary public-access network.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Meanwhile, working independently, a team led by Douglas Engelbart (with Jeff Rulifson as chief programmer) was the first to implement the hyperlink concept for scrolling within a single document (1966), and soon after for connecting between paragraphs within separate documents (1968), with NLS.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Ben Shneiderman working with graduate student Dan Ostroff designed and implemented the highlighted link in the HyperTIES system in 1983.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] HyperTIES was used to produce the world's first electronic journal, the July 1988 Communications of the ACM, which was cited as the source for the link concept in Tim Berners-Lee's Spring 1989 manifesto for the Web.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In 1988, Ben Shneiderman and Greg Kearsley used HyperTIES to publish "Hypertext Hands-On!", the world's first electronic book.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Released in 1987 for the Apple Macintosh, the database program HyperCard allowed for hyperlinking between various pages within a document, as well as to other documents and separate applications on the same computer.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The first widely used open protocol that included hyperlinks from any Internet site to any other Internet site was the Gopher protocol from 1991.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] It was soon eclipsed by HTML after the 1993 release of the Mosaic browser (which could handle Gopher links as well as HTML links).
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] HTML's advantage was the ability to mix graphics, text, and hyperlinks, unlike Gopher, which just had menu-structured text and hyperlinks.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] While hyperlinking among webpages is an intrinsic feature of the web, some websites object to being linked by other websites; some have claimed that linking to them is not allowed without permission.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In certain jurisdictions, it is or has been held that hyperlinks are not merely references or citations, but are devices for copying web pages.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In the Netherlands, Karin Spaink was initially convicted in this way of copyright infringement by linking, although this ruling was overturned in 2003.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] The courts that advocate this view see the mere publication of a hyperlink that connects to illegal material to be an illegal act in itself, regardless of whether referencing illegal material is illegal.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In 2000, British Telecom sued Prodigy, claiming that Prodigy infringed its patent (U.S. patent 4,873,662) on web hyperlinks.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] After litigation, a court found for Prodigy, ruling that British Telecom's patent did not cover web hyperlinks.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] In United States *jurisprudence*, there is a distinction between the mere act of linking to someone else's website, and linking to content that is illegal (e.g., gambling illegal in the US) or infringing (e.g., illegal MP3 copies).
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Several courts have found that merely linking to someone else's website, even if by bypassing commercial advertising, is not copyright or trademark infringement, regardless of how much someone else might object.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Linking to illegal or infringing content can be sufficiently problematic to give rise to legal liability.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Compare for a summary of the current status of US copyright law as to hyperlinking, see the discussion regarding the *Arriba Soft* and *Perfect 10* cases.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hyperlink] Somewhat controversially, Vuestar Technologies has tried to enforce patents applied for by its owner, Ronald Neville Langford, around the world relating to search techniques using hyperlinked images to other websites or web pages.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hypertext-application-language] HAL was created to be simple to use and easily applicable across different domains by avoiding the need to impose any requirements on how the project be structured.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hypertext-application-language] Maintaining this minimal impact approach, HAL has enabled developers to create general-purpose libraries which can be incorporated on any API that uses HAL.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hypertext-application-language] APIs that adopt HAL simplify the use of open source libraries and make it possible to interact with the API using JSON or XML.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hypertext-application-language] The alternative would be having to develop a proprietary format which in turn forces developers to learn how to use yet another foreign format.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hypertext-application-language] HAL is structured in such a way as to represent elements based on two concepts: Resources and Links.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hypertext-application-language] Resources consist of URI links, embedded resources, your standard data (be it JSON or XML), and non URI links.
[src:hal-hypermedia/hypertext-application-language] Links have a target URI, as well as the name of the link (referred to as 'rel'), as well as optional properties designed to be mindful of deprecation and content negotiation.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] In information and communications technology, a **media type**, **content type** or **MIME type** is a two-part identifier for file formats and content formats.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Their purpose is comparable to filename extensions and uniform type identifiers, in that they identify the intended data format.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] They are mainly used by technologies underpinning the Internet, and also used on Linux desktop systems.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) is the official authority for the standardization and publication of these classifications.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Media types are also used by other internet protocols such as HTTP, document file formats such as HTML, and the XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments, for similar purposes.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Different internet standards or web standards bodies differ on the preferred term for this type of identifier.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The IANA and IETF use the term "media type", and consider the term "MIME type" to be obsolete, since media types have become used in contexts unrelated to email, such as HTTP.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] By contrast, the WHATWG continues to use the term "MIME type" and discourages use of the term "media type" as ambiguous, since it is used with a different meaning in connection with the CSS `@media` feature.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The HTTP response header for providing the media type is `Content-Type`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The W3C has used `ContentType` as an XML data-type name for a media type.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments continue to use the term "MIME type".
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] A media type consists of a *type* and a *subtype*, which is further structured into a *tree*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] As an example, an HTML file might be designated `text/html; charset=UTF-8`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] In this example, `text` is the type, `html` is the subtype, and `charset=UTF-8` is an optional parameter indicating the character encoding.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Types, subtypes, and parameter names are case-insensitive.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Parameter values are usually case-sensitive, but may be interpreted in a case-insensitive fashion depending on the intended use.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The "type" part defines the broad use of the media type.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] As of November 1996, the registered types were `application`, `audio`,`image`, `message`, `multipart`, `text` and `video`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] By July 2024, the registered types included the foregoing, plus `font`, `example`, `model`, and `haptics`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] An unofficial top-level type in common use is `chemical`, used for chemical file formats.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] A subtype typically consists of a media format, but it may or must also contain other content, such as a tree prefix, producer, product or suffix, according to the different rules in registration trees.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] All media types should be registered using the IANA registration procedures.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] For the efficiency and flexibility of the media type registration process, different structures of subtypes can be registered in registration trees that are distinguished by the use of tree prefixes.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Currently, the following trees are created: standard (no prefix), vendor (`vnd.` prefix), personal or vanity (`prs.` prefix), unregistered (`x.` prefix).
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] These registration trees were first defined in November 1996 (obsoleted RFC 2048 - currently RFC 6838).
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] New registration trees may be created by IETF Standards Action for external registration and management by well-known permanent organizations (e.g. scientific societies).
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The standards tree does not use any tree prefix.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Examples are `text/javascript`, `image/png`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Registrations in the standards tree must be either associated with IETF specifications approved directly by the IESG, or registered by an IANA recognized standards-related organization.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The vendor tree includes media types associated with publicly available products.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Examples are: `application/vnd.ms-excel`, `application/vnd.oasis.opendocument.text`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The terms "vendor" and "producer" are considered equivalent in the context.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Industry consortia as well as non-commercial entities can register media types in the vendor tree.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] A registration in the vendor tree may be created by anyone who needs to interchange files associated with some software product or set of products.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] However, the registration belongs to the vendor or organization producing the software that employs the type being registered, and that vendor or organization can at any time elect to assert ownership of a registration done by a third party.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The personal or vanity tree includes media types associated with non publicly available products or experimental media types.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Examples are `audio/prs.sid`, `image/prs.btif`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The unregistered tree includes media types intended exclusively for use in private environments and only with the active agreement of the parties exchanging them.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Examples are `application/x.foo`, `video/x.bar`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Media types in this tree cannot be registered.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] This type was originally defined in RFC 1590 (published in September 1993) using the `x-` or `X-` prefix.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] RFC 2048 (published in November 1996) introduced the `x.` prefix, but discouraged use of the unregistered tree, as new personal and vendor trees with relaxed registration requirements are now available.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The current RFC 6838 (published in January 2013) maintains the same recommendation, but subtypes prefixed with `x-` or `X-` are no longer considered to be members of this tree.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Media types that have been widely deployed (with a subtype prefixed with `x-` or `X-`) without being registered, should be, if possible, re-registered with a proper prefixed subtype.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] If this is not possible, the media type can, after an approval by both the media types reviewer and the IESG, be registered in the standards tree with its unprefixed subtype.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` is an example of a widely deployed type that ended up registered with the `x-` prefix.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Suffix is an augmentation to the media type definition to additionally specify the underlying structure of that media type, allowing for generic processing based on that structure and independent of the exact type's particular semantics.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Media types that make use of a named structured syntax should use the appropriate IANA registered `"+"suffix` for that structured syntax when they are registered.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Unregistered suffixes should not be used (since January 2013).
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Structured syntax suffix registration procedures are defined in RFC 6838.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The +xml suffix has been defined since January 2001 (RFC 3023), and was formally included in the initial contents of the Structured Syntax Suffix Registry along with `+json`, `+ber`, `+der`, `+fastinfoset`, `+wbxml`, and `+zip` in January 2013 (RFC 6839).
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Subsequent additions include `+gzip`, `+cbor`, `+json-seq`, and `+cbor-seq`.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Mailcap (derived from the phrase "mail capability") is a type of meta file used to configure how MIME-aware applications such as mail clients and web browsers render files of different MIME-types.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] The mailcap format is defined by RFC 1524 "A User Agent Configuration Mechanism for Multimedia Mail Format Information" but is not defined as an Internet standard.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Lines can be comments starting with the # character, or a mime-type followed by how to handle that mime type.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] An associated file is the **mime.types** file, which associates filename extensions with a *MIME type*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] If the MIME type is properly set, this is unnecessary, but MIME types may be incorrectly set, or set to a generic type such as `application/octet-stream`, and **mime.types** allows one to fall back on the extension in these cases.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] Similarly, since many file systems do not store MIME type information, but instead rely on the filename extension, a mime.types file is frequently used by web servers to determine MIME type.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] When *viewing* a file, these two work together as follows: **`mime.types`** associates an extension with a MIME type, while `mailcap` associates a MIME type with a program.
[src:hal-hypermedia/media-type] In UNIX-type systems, the mime.types file is usually located at `/etc/**mime.types**` and/or `$HOME/**.mime.types**` and the format is simply that each line is a space-delimited list of a MIME type, followed by zero or more extensions.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:hal-hypermedia/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:hal-hypermedia/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
